  <span id="freeText4776862800435601352" style="display:none">Walter Tevis sure as hell ain't no one-trick-pony. After falling in love with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3610890993" rel="nofollow noopener">The Queen's Gambit</a>, I was keen to explore his science fiction work and this is a wonderfully successful contribution to the genre. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1608890823i/30585360.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>Mockingbird</i> is the surprising story about humanity, fears of technology and happiness explored through a set of humans and robots. Set in the near future, we're presented a world in which robots do our work for us – sounds idyllic, doesn't it?<br><br><b>His themes are as relevant today as they were in the 80s, when this was first published.</b> With AI advancing as exponentially fast as it is today, the questions of how intelligent Artificial Intelligence should truly become and as what point the helpful becomes the harmful is as valid a question as it is an important one. In Tevis's world, humanity has steered itself into extinction by sheer laziness: for the people in here, it just became too handy to lean back and just <i>entertain yourself</i> while others do the work. <br><br><b>This is as much dystopian as it is a love letter to the power of reading.</b> In this world, people can no longer read. They have simply forgotten how to do it, and it's only when Robert, a university professor, begins to realise that the films he's secretly been studying have subtitles that match what the people are saying that the written word is rediscovered. With the world of fiction suddenly opened up to him, he's slowly able to question the ideals that he's been taught – that <i>privacy</i> is most important, that <i>quick sex is best</i>. <br><br><b>
  <i>"Don’t you want to be happy?"</i>
</b><br><br><b>There's the irony of the dilemma between knowledge and happiness.</b> Can we be curious and fulfilled? The story of Robert proves that the more you know, the more you question existing constitutions and the more likely you're to find faults in the <i>status quo</i>. Is it worth giving up purpose in order to live a happy, yet ignorant life? This novel presents a world in which people have answered this question with a <i>yes</i> and let me tell you, I am terrified. </span>
