  <span id="freeText16288445417697617814" style="display:none">I recently reread “Mockingbird” (1980), which was the first Water Tevis novel I had read. I had seen some of the movies made from his work: “The Hustler”, “The Color of Money” and “The Man Who Fell to Earth” starring David Bowie. I read (somewhere) that Mr. Tevis’ inspiration for this work was based on his experience as a school teacher (he never did quit his day-job it seems) noticing that the students of his later days in the field, seemed less capable of reading and writing that they had been in earlier times. As any science fiction writer does, he projected this decline into the future to set this story, in New York city, during a time when human-shaped bio-robots dominate the world while the human population in its bleakest state: mostly illiterate, depressed, indifferent; they are perpetually drugged and suicidal for various reasons, and also, women have become sterile - by taking the very drug that helps them cope with the utter hopelessness of their current existence.<br /><br />Though far from the hard scifi that was ‘a la mode’ during the time this was published - when the works of Niven, Benford, Brin and Pournelle dominated the scene - this is a fine and engaging tale laced with great insights of the human condition. Despite a few clunky bits, I enjoyed it even more on second reading than the first. It is one of those books that I often recall quite vividly. Those rare atmospheric books that stick with you forever.</span>
