  <span id="freeText10510845949680934723" style="display:none">Mockingbird is Walter Tevis' dystopian story of humanity's folly, near demise, and hope for the future.<br /><br />Connectedness is a primary theme of the book. People have been conditioned from an early age to value inward fulfillment and privacy and shun most social contact. The conditioning is both chemical and trained, and while isolation is not presented as voluntary, I felt like Tevis lays blame for many problems at the feet of society. I would personally not need training, drugs, or even a gentle suggestion to self-isolate. On the contrary, Tevis' dystopian New York sounded great to me. Where do I sign up?<br /><br />Apathy is another primary theme of the book. People are doped and trained to "don't ask, relax," but the drugs are not mandatory. I thought this theme was well discussed, and I agree that widespread intoxication dependence is a sign of an unwell society. Tevis also expressed a rare and surprisingly empathetic view of suicide. Sometimes people simply don't want to live anymore. Kudos to Tevis for not lumping a desire to escape a miserable existence in with mental illness. I feel like our society has incredibly selfish and hypocritical viewpoints on this topic, and it's refreshing to read a book that treats it more honestly.<br /><br />The perils of over-reliance on technology are also in sharp focus. In Mockingbird, humans had every technological solution imaginable, but couldn't quite bring themselves to treat each other well. Tevis states that this basic inability to interact without violence is what led to systematic doping. The practice of electing homicidal maniacs to do anonymous violence is also called on the carpet. In short, humans cannot be trusted to rule themselves, or even interact peacefully, so society's administration is turned over to robots who dope them into compliance. <br /><br />As with another dystopian favorite of mine, This Perfect Day by Ira Levin, I am not in total disagreement with the presented "dystopia." If humans have proven one thing beyond a doubt, it is that we have a dark side to our nature that can only result in a violent extinction. Mockingbird presents this idea unambiguously and convingly.<br /><br />As with most dystopian stories, a ray of hope shines through the dark clouds in the end.<br /><br />A true sci-fi classic, recommended to everyone.</span>
